@chergert Thank you for pointing this out. 

My suggestion is to check if the current buffer is empty since the modified bit gets set even when the document is empty. If the buffer is indeed empty, we can manually unset the modified bit to differentiate between truly empty buffers and those modified accidentally or intentionally.

Does this approach sound reasonable, or would you suggest an alternative?

With this, I am able to close the "Document Type" popup on pressing `ESC` key:

```c
// editor-language-dialog.c
...
static void
editor_language_dialog_search_stop_cb   (EditorLanguageDialog *self)
{
  g_assert (EDITOR_IS_LANGUAGE_DIALOG (self));

  adw_dialog_close (&self -> parent_instance);
}
...
```
attached a demo for the same:  
![Recording](/uploads/5f9ec607cb60a569519b78b4c164460b/Recording.gif)

@chergert let me know if this is fine.

Here too. `{` on newlines and since these are conditionals, indented 2 more spaces like this:

```c
if (thing)
  {
    ...
  }
else if (other_thing)
  {
  }
```

I know it's awkward, but we try to keep things consistent.

Okay, I cannot reproduce this with GtkSourceView directly, but I also find something extremely interesting.

```patch
diff --git a/src/editor-document.c b/src/editor-document.c
index ce0ded5..cdfd591 100644
--- a/src/editor-document.c
+++ b/src/editor-document.c
@@ -661,6 +661,28 @@ editor_document_set_property (GObject      *object,
     }
 }

+static void
+editor_document_apply_tag (GtkTextBuffer     *buffer,
+                           GtkTextTag        *tag,
+                           const GtkTextIter *begin,
+                           const GtkTextIter *end)
+{
+  g_autofree char *name = NULL;
+
+  g_assert (GTK_IS_TEXT_BUFFER (buffer));
+  g_assert (GTK_IS_TEXT_TAG (tag));
+  g_assert (begin != NULL);
+  g_assert (end != NULL);
+
+  g_object_get (tag, "name", &name, NULL);
+
+  g_print ("Apply tag: %s %u:%u\n", name,
+           gtk_text_iter_get_offset (begin),
+           gtk_text_iter_get_offset (end));
+
+  GTK_TEXT_BUFFER_CLASS (editor_document_parent_class)->apply_tag (buffer, tag, begin, end);
+}
+
 static void
 editor_document_class_init (EditorDocumentClass *klass)
 {
@@ -675,6 +697,7 @@ editor_document_class_init (EditorDocumentClass *klass)
   buffer_class->changed = editor_document_changed;
   buffer_class->insert_text = editor_document_insert_text;
   buffer_class->delete_range = editor_document_delete_range;
+  buffer_class->apply_tag = editor_document_apply_tag;

   properties [PROP_SUGGEST_ADMIN] =
     g_param_spec_boolean ("suggest-admin",
```

If we patch EditorDocument to notify us about all buffer changes, we can see that there is absolutely no tag change causing `hello` to be highlighted.

That almost certainly means there is a bug somewhere in `GtkTextLayout` in GTK directly that is causing this styling to hangover.

I have no idea though, why that would show up in Text Editor and not GtkSourceView directly.

The only tag which is applied, is this:

```
Apply tag: (null) 0:9
```

which is definitely correct.
